{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529813"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:58:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:58:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14460"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14460"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.13,0.05,0.67,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7155"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56130"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7155"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14460"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41682"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1519"},{"type":"tags","id":"2943"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17194"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56130"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 84-year-old woman is admitted to the geriatric medical ward with a urinary tract infection and acute confusion. She has a medical history of mixed dementia, urinary incontinence, osteoarthritis, and hypothyroidism. Her regular medications include cholecalciferol, donepezil, oxybutynin, paracetamol, and levothyroxine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly dehydrated with dry mucous membranes and reduced skin turgor. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 135/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. The rest of her clinical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 75 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 65 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;60)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETSH: 2.5 mU/L (0.4-4.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFree T4: 16 pmol/L (10-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECorrected calcium: 3.1 mmol/L (2.2-2.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParathyroid hormone: 0.6 pmol/L (1.6-6.9)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral bisphosphonates","Calcitonin injection","Vitamin D supplementation","Intravenous fluids","Parathyroidectomy referral"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with hypercalcaemia (corrected calcium 3.1 mmol/L) in the context of a urinary tract infection and dehydration. The parathyroid hormone (PTH) level is below the normal range and given the high calcium level, this suggests a non-PTH mediated cause of hypercalcaemia, such as malignancy or vitamin D toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous fluids\u003C/strong\u003E are the most appropriate first step in management. Hypercalcaemia causes polyuria and subsequent dehydration, which in turn worsens hypercalcaemia by increasing calcium reabsorption in the kidneys. Rehydration with intravenous fluids helps to correct this vicious cycle and is the mainstay of initial treatment for hypercalcaemia, particularly when there are signs of dehydration as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral bisphosphonates\u003C/strong\u003E can be used in the treatment of hypercalcaemia, but they are not the first-line treatment, especially in acute settings. They are more commonly used for long-term management of hypercalcaemia due to malignancy or other chronic conditions. The use of intravenous bisphosphonates is well established as management in severe, symptomatic hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcitonin injection\u003C/strong\u003E can rapidly lower serum calcium levels, but its effect is short-lived and it is usually reserved for severe, symptomatic hypercalcaemia in conjunction with other treatments. It is not the most appropriate first-line treatment in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParathyroidectomy referral\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if primary hyperparathyroidism was suspected. However, in this case, the PTH level is suppressed, making primary hyperparathyroidism unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin D supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in hypercalcaemia, as it could potentially worsen the condition. In fact, vitamin D toxicity should be considered as a possible cause of the hypercalcaemia in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initial management with intravenous fluids, the next steps would include further investigation to determine the underlying cause of the hypercalcaemia. This might include checking vitamin D levels, searching for occult malignancy (e.g., with chest X-ray, mammography, or CT scanning), and reviewing all medications and supplements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypercalcaemia with a low or normal parathyroid hormone level suggests non-parathyroid hormone mediated causes, such as malignancy or vitamin D toxicity.","Intravenous fluids are the first-line treatment for hypercalcaemia, especially in the context of dehydration.","Further investigation of the underlying cause of hypercalcaemia is crucial, particularly in older adults where malignancy is a common cause."],"references":["Tonon CR, Silva TAAL, Pereira FWL, et al. A Review of Current Clinical Concepts in the Pathophysiology, Etiology, Diagnosis, and Management of Hypercalcemia. Med Sci Monit. 2022;28:e935821. Published 2022 Feb 26. doi:10.12659/MSM.935821. Available online at ; https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8889795/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41682"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14460"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41682"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T17:00:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T17:04:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7155"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56130"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/152"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cystitis","synonyms":["Urinary tract infection","UTI","Lower UTI","Urinary infection","Urinary tract infections"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T14:37:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1172"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"EUC","synonyms":["Electrolytes urea creatinine","UEC","Renal function tests","RFTs","Urea/electrolytes/creatinine","Electrolytes/urea/creatinine","Biochemistry"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-07-28T11:34:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-11T10:56:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"4"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1519","links":{"self":"https://app.